04528nam a22007335i 9780231554305DE-B159720220426115627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220426t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021047076  a97802315543057 a10.7312/shir201862doi  a(DE-B1597)624620  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJC328.6b.S54 2022 4aJC328.6b.S54 2022 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a303.6223/eng/202111021 aShirk, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking War on the World :bHow Transnational Violence Reshapes Global Order /cMark Shirk. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in International Order and Politics00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. CHANGE AND CONTINUITY IN POLITICAL ORDER -- t2. THE GOLDEN AGE OF PIRACY AND THE CREATION OF AN ATLANTIC WORLD -- t3. “PROPAGANDA OF THE DEED,” SURVEILLANCE, AND THE LABOR MOVEMENT -- t4. AL- QAEDA, THE WAR ON TERROR, AND THE BOUNDARIES OF THE TWENTY- FIRST CENTURY -- tCONCLUSION -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe state bounds politics: it constructs and enforces boundaries that separate what it controls from what lies outside its domain. However, states face a variety of threats that cross and challenge their geographical and conceptual boundaries. Transnational violent actors that transcend these boundaries also defy the state’s claims to political authority and legitimacy.Mark Shirk examines historical and contemporary state responses to transnational violence to develop a new account of the making of global orders. He considers a series of crises that plagued the state system in different eras: golden-age piracy in the eighteenth century, anarchist “propagandists of the deed” at the turn of the twentieth, and al-Qaeda in recent years. Shirk argues that states redraw conceptual boundaries, such as between “international” and “domestic,” to make sense of and defeat transnational threats. In response to forms of political violence that challenged boundaries, states developed creative responses that included new forms of control, surveillance, and rights. As a result, these responses gradually made and transformed the state and global order. Shirk draws on extensive archival research and interviews with policy makers and experts, and he explores the implications for understandings of state formation. Combining rich detail and theoretical insight, Making War on the World reveals the role of pirates, anarchists, and terrorists in shaping global order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aAnarchism. 0aNational security. 0aNon-state actors (International relations)xHistory. 0aPiracy. 0aPolitical violencexHistory. 0aSecurity, International. 0aTransnationalism. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/shir2018640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231554305423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231554305/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK